Great question. Understanding the startup log is very useful because it tells you **what Spring Boot is doing step by step**.

---

# Spring Boot Banner

```text
  .   ____          _            __ _ _
 /\\ / ___'_ __ _ _(_)_ __  __ _ \ \ \ \
...
:: Spring Boot ::                (v3.1.6)
```

This is just the **Spring Boot logo**.

It also tells you the version:

```text
Spring Boot 3.1.6
```

Nothing is happening here except printing a welcome banner.

---

# 1. Starting the application

```text
Starting DigitalBankApplication using Java 17.0.19
```

### Meaning

Spring Boot starts running your project.

It also tells you:

* Main class:

  ```
  DigitalBankApplication
  ```

* Java version:

  ```
  Java 17
  ```

---

# 2. Active profile

```text
No active profile set, falling back to 1 default profile: "default"
```

### Meaning

Spring supports **Profiles**.

Example:

```text
Development
Testing
Production
```

Each profile can have different settings.

Since you didn't specify one, Spring uses

```text
default
```

---

# 3. Repository scanning

```text
Bootstrapping Spring Data JPA repositories
```

### Meaning

Spring starts searching for interfaces like

```java
public interface CustomerRepository
```

or

```java
public interface BankAccountRepository
```

---

Then

```text
Found 3 JPA repository interfaces.
```

means

Spring found

```
CustomerRepository
BankAccountRepository
TransactionRepository
```

and creates implementations automatically.

---

# 4. Tomcat

```text
Tomcat initialized with port(s): 8080
```

### Meaning

Spring starts the embedded web server.

Instead of installing Tomcat separately,

Spring Boot starts one itself.

Port

```
8080
```

means

```
http://localhost:8080
```

---

# 5. Starting Service

```text
Starting service [Tomcat]
```

Meaning

Tomcat is starting.

---

# 6. Starting Servlet Engine

```text
Starting Servlet engine
```

Servlet is the technology that receives HTTP requests.

Example

```
GET /Customer/1
```

The Servlet receives it and passes it to Spring.

---

# 7. WebApplicationContext

```text
Initializing Spring embedded WebApplicationContext
```

This is one of the most important steps.

Think of it as Spring creating a huge container.

Inside this container it stores every object like

```
CustomerService

CustomerRepository

CustomerController

BankAccountService

TransactionService
```

This container is called the **Spring Container**.

---

# 8. Context completed

```text
Root WebApplicationContext: initialization completed
```

Meaning

Spring finished creating all Beans.

Everything is ready.

---

# 9. Hibernate

```text
Processing PersistenceUnitInfo
```

Meaning

Hibernate starts.

Hibernate now searches for

```java
@Entity
```

classes.

For example

```
Customer

BankAccount

Transaction
```

---

# 10. Hibernate version

```text
Hibernate ORM core version 6.2.13.Final
```

Just tells you the version.

---

# 11. Bytecode Reflection Optimizer

```text
Using bytecode reflection optimizer
```

Meaning

Hibernate uses an optimization technique to make entity access faster.

You normally don't need to worry about this.

---

# 12. LoadTimeWeaver

```text
No LoadTimeWeaver setup
```

Meaning

Spring checked whether advanced bytecode weaving is enabled.

It isn't.

This is completely normal.

---

# 13. HikariCP

```text
Customer - Starting...
```

HikariCP is the **connection pool**.

Instead of opening a new database connection every request,

it keeps several ready.

---

Then

```text
Added connection
```

means

Spring successfully connected to MySQL.

---

Then

```text
Start completed
```

means

Database connection is ready.

---

# 14. JTA Platform

```text
No JTA platform available
```

JTA is used for distributed transactions involving multiple databases or messaging systems.

You have only one database.

So this is perfectly fine.

---

# 15. EntityManagerFactory

```text
Initialized JPA EntityManagerFactory
```

This is another very important object.

The `EntityManagerFactory` creates `EntityManager` objects.

The `EntityManager` is responsible for operations such as:

* Save entities
* Find entities
* Update entities
* Delete entities

Repositories use it internally.

---

# 16. Warning

```text
spring.jpa.open-in-view is enabled
```

This is only a warning.

Spring keeps the database session open while generating the HTTP response.

For learning projects, you can ignore it.

---

# 17. Tomcat started

```text
Tomcat started on port(s): 8080
```

Meaning

Your web server is now accepting requests.

You can open:

```
http://localhost:8080
```

---

# 18. Started Application

```text
Started DigitalBankApplication in 4.549 seconds
```

Meaning

Everything started successfully.

Your application is now running.

---

# Complete startup flow

```text
1. Start Spring Boot
        │
        ▼
2. Read application.properties
        │
        ▼
3. Find Controllers
        │
        ▼
4. Find Services
        │
        ▼
5. Find Repositories
        │
        ▼
6. Connect to MySQL
        │
        ▼
7. Hibernate scans @Entity classes
        │
        ▼
8. Create/Update tables (if needed)
        │
        ▼
9. Start Tomcat
        │
        ▼
10. Application ready
```

